<h1><a href="/~theory/269/">ICS 269, Winter 2002: Theory Seminar</a></h1>

<hr>
<h2>28 Feb 2003:<br>
Is Edge-Expansion Robust to Random Faults?<br>
Amitabh Bagchi</h2>

<p>Consider the situation where nodes of a graph <i>G</i> become faulty
independently with probability <i>p</i> giving the graph
<i>G<sub>p</sub></i>. The "critical
probability" <i>p</i><sup>*</sup> for a graph is defined as that value
of <i>p</i> for which
there is no linear sized component remaining in the graph
<i>G</i><sub><i>p</i><sup>*</sup></sub> with high
probability. We call a graph parameter &rho;(<i>G</i>) "robust" if
&rho;(<i>G</i><sub><i>p</i><sup>*</sup>-o(<i>p</i><sup>*</sup>)</sub>)&nbsp;=&nbsp;&theta;(&rho;(<i>G</i>)) i.e. if the value of &rho; is preserved upto a
constant factor till the point where the graph itself falls apart.</p>

We consider the robustness of a graph parameter important to the study
of the routing properties of a network: the edge expansion. We prove a
general theorem from which the robustness of edge expansion on a mesh
can be deduced.

